","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":105,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":114,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Richard Ashburnham was born about 1110, in England. She had at least 1 son with Richard Ashburnham."},"et":{"about 1110–":"umbes 1110–Surnud","1110–1166":"1110–1166","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","about 1110":"umbes 1110","about 1130":"umbes 1130","England":"England","Ashburnham, Sussex, England":"Ashburnham, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1110–":"noin 1110–Kuollut","1110–1166":"1110–1166","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1110–Female":"1110–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","about 1110":"noin 1110","about 1130":"noin 1130","England":"England","Ashburnham, Sussex, England":"Ashburnham, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1110–":"environ 1110–Décédée","1110–1166":"1110–1166","1130–Male":"1130–Décédé","1110–Female":"1110–Décédée","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","about 1110":"environ 1110","about 1130":"environ 1130","England":"Angleterre","Ashburnham, Sussex, England":"Ashburnham, Sussex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs Richard Ashburnham est née environ 1110, à Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Richard Ashburnham."},"de":{"about 1110–":"um 1110–Verstorben","1110–1166":"1110–1166","1130–Male":"1130–Verstorben","1110–Female":"1110–Verstorben","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","about 1110":"um 1110","about 1130":"um 1130","England":"England","Ashburnham, Sussex, England":"Ashburnham, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Mrs Richard Ash